Description: Stamp-seal carved from stone; with oval device on base deeply incised with plant (palm branch?); narrow top with suspension loop now snapped off; in grey stone, smoothly polished.
Curator's comments: Floral motifs such as this one are difficult to date. Combined with the overal shape of the seal, it is likely not earlier than the Late Period but examples are still attested into the Late Roman period in Egypt (Teeter 2003, 197, pl. 106a, no. 320, with various parallels). The possibility that it is an imported seal should also be considered with grey limestone (if the identification of the material is correct) pointing towards a possible Cypriot origin. Teeter, E. 2003, Scarabs, scaraboids, seals, and seal impressions from Medinet Habu; with post-pharaonic stamp seals and seal impressions, Chicago.
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (PA.17) (phase 3)
Condition: incomplete - the upper portion has broken away
